    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-07-26T18:01:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-07-26T18:01:00-05:00" n="236"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d236">
                <head>236. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Vietnam</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d236fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 396.1–GE/7–2655. Secret. Drafted by <persName>Byrne</persName>.
                        Repeated for information to Phnom Penh, Vientiane, New Delhi, Ottawa, Paris,
                        and London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-07-26T18:01:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 26, 1955—6:01 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>293. …</p>
                <p>When <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> brought up Vietnamese
                    elections [at the <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName>–<persName
                        corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> talks held in Geneva on July 23]
                        <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> stated British had always
                    suggested consultations and U.S. <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> France had
                    agreed recommend Vietnamese Government answer <persName corresp="#p_PVD1"
                        >Dong</persName> letter. <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> had
                    seen report of agreement in press.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Macmillan</persName> declared <gloss target="#t_UK1"
                        >UK</gloss> would do best see Geneva Accords fully implemented and
                    consultations undertaken.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> doubted two co-Chairmen should send
                    communication other Geneva signatories. <persName corresp="#p_MVM1"
                        >Molotov</persName> did not dissent. British thought preferable co-Chairmen
                    maintain close contact two parties Viet-Nam, Indians and each other. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> appeared accept idea of telegram to
                        <persName corresp="#p_NPJ1">Nehru</persName> in this sense.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> stated he would send <persName
                        corresp="#p_NPJ1">Nehru</persName> own account conversation and asked
                    whether <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> would object <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>’s informing “Chinese” Government.
                        <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> said no.</p>
                <pb facs="0530" n="498" xml:id="pg_498"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> commented atmosphere calm and not
                    unfriendly. Both sides agreed world not so close to war as last summer.</p>
                <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
